******
[1] Texas
Date: Wed 3 Jul 2019 12:00 pm CDT
Source: My San Antonio [edited]
http://www.mysanantonio.com/text-alerts/


An Aransas county man has had 3 surgeries and is still in the hospital after he contracted _Vibrio_, a flesh-eating bacterium, while fishing on Ransom Island near Aransas Pass, according to a recent story from KRIS 6 NEWS. Shortly after a fishing trip, a 79-year-old was admitted into the hospital because of a cut on his hand that was also swollen, his daughter told KRIS 6 NEWS. He had been fishing with his son-in-law.

This is the 2nd flesh-eating incident that has been reported after visits to South Texas beaches. A Corpus Christi man underwent several life-saving surgeries after he contracted vibriosis from dipping his toes into the water near Waters Edge Park in Corpus Christi. The man, 42, didn't have any open wounds at the time, which the _Vibrio_ bacterium typically use as an entry into the body. His right toe, however, was infected with fungus, creating an opening between his skin and toenail, according to a mySA article.

According to the CDC, about 80 000 people a year are infected with vibriosis. The bacteria live in coastal waters and increase concentration when the water warms between May and October. People can also become infected by consuming undercooked or raw seafood.

[Byline: Priscilla Aguirre]

